    slug: "dhari-aur-khizab",
    description: `Dhari Aur Khizab is an Urdu-language Islamic book that provides a comprehensive and detailed discussion of the Islamic rulings concerning the beard (dhari) and the cutting or trimming of hair and nails (khizab), drawing upon the Quran, the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), and the consensus of the classical scholars to establish the importance of the beard as a Sunnah of the Prophet and a distinguishing marker of Muslim men. The book addresses what has become a contentious topic in contemporary Muslim societies, where the practice of growing a full beard has been challenged by cultural assimilation, modern fashion trends, and differing scholarly opinions, and it aims to present the evidences clearly so that readers can make an informed decision based on authentic Islamic sources rather than cultural pressure or personal preference.

The book begins by establishing the foundational evidences from the Quran and the Sunnah that support the obligation or strong recommendation of growing the beard. It presents the key hadith on this topic, including the well-known narration in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) said, "Trim the moustache and save the beard" (Sahih al-Bukhari), and the narration in which the Prophet (peace be upon him) commanded the Muslims to "be different from the polytheists: let your beards grow and trim your moustaches" (Sahih Muslim). The author examines each hadith with its full chain of narration, discusses the grading by hadith scholars, and explains the various opinions of the four major schools of Islamic jurisprudence (Hanafi, Maliki, Shafi'i, and Hanbali) regarding the legal status of the beard. The differences of opinion are presented fairly and with proper scholarly references, allowing readers to understand the spectrum of views within mainstream Sunni scholarship.

The second part of the book, addressing khizab (cutting, trimming, or removing hair and nails), covers the Islamic rulings on personal grooming for both men and women. It discusses the Sunnah method of removing unwanted hair, the timing of grooming according to the Prophetic recommendations (such as trimming the nails every forty days), and the specific prohibitions related to certain types of hair removal or styling that imitate non-Muslim practices or violate the principles of modesty. The book also addresses the related topic of the prohibition of women cutting their hair in styles that resemble men and men styling themselves in ways that resemble women. The Urdu prose is scholarly yet accessible, with full references to the original Arabic sources and the major fiqh manuals. This book is a valuable resource for imams, students of Islamic knowledge, and any Muslim who wants to understand the Islamic perspective on personal grooming and appearance based on authentic evidence.`,
