    slug: "dua-or-dum-kay-zariye-masnoon-elaj",
    description: `Dua Or Dum Kay Zariye Masnoon Elaj is an Urdu-language book that provides a comprehensive guide to the Prophetic method of spiritual healing through dua (supplication) and dum (blowing over the patient after reciting Quranic verses and authentic duas), drawing upon the authentic hadith of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to establish the correct Islamic approach to treating illness and affliction through spiritual means. The title translates to "Prophetic Healing Through Dua and Dum," and the book addresses a topic that is of great interest and importance to Urdu-speaking Muslim communities, where the practice of ruqyah (spiritual healing) is widespread but often mixed with innovations, superstitions, and practices that have no basis in the authentic Sunnah.

The book begins by establishing the Islamic theological foundation for spiritual healing, explaining that all healing ultimately comes from Allah alone and that the use of dua, dum, and ruqyah are means (asbab) through which Allah grants healing, not independent causes in themselves. The author carefully distinguishes between the authentic Prophetic practice of ruqyah, which involves reciting specific verses of the Quran and authentic duas and then blowing over the patient, and the many innovated or superstitious practices that are commonly associated with spiritual healing in South Asian Muslim culture, such as the use of amulets (taweez) containing incomprehensible symbols, the invocation of spirits or jinn, the sacrifice of animals for non-Islamic purposes, and the charging of money for healing services that are presented as having supernatural power independent of Allah.

The core of the book is a detailed compilation of the specific duas and Quranic verses that have been authentically narrated from the Prophet (peace be upon him) for the purpose of healing. These include Surah Al-Fatihah (which the Prophet described as the greatest healing), Ayat al-Kursi (the Verse of the Throne), the last two surahs of the Quran (Al-Falaq and An-Nas, which the Prophet used for ruqyah), the dua of Ayyub (Job) for healing from illness, the dua for visiting the sick, the dua for protection from various diseases and afflictions, and many other specific supplications for different types of ailments. For each dua, the book provides the full Arabic text, the Urdu translation, the reference to the hadith source, and instructions on how it should be used in the practice of dum. The book also covers the conditions and etiquette of performing ruqyah, including the requirement that the person performing ruqyah must have firm faith in Allah alone as the healer, that the patient must believe in the efficacy of the ruqyah, and that the content of the ruqyah must be limited to the Quran and authentic Sunnah. This book is an essential reference for anyone who wants to practice or receive ruqyah in accordance with the authentic Prophetic methodology.`,
