    slug: "english-translation-of-sunan-ibn-majah-5-volumes-set",
    description: `English Translation of Sunan Ibn Majah — 5 Volumes Set is the complete English translation of Sunan Ibn Majah, the fifth of the six canonical hadith collections (Kutub as-Sittah) recognized in Sunni Islam, originally compiled by Imam Muhammad ibn Yazid Ibn Majah al-Qazvini (209-273 AH / 824-887 CE). Sunan Ibn Majah contains over 4,341 narrations and is known for including hadith that are not found in the other five canonical collections, which gives it a unique value as a hadith source even though some of its narrations are classified as weak by hadith scholars. The collection covers a broad range of topics related to Islamic belief, practice, law, and morality, and its inclusion in the Kutub as-Sittah by the consensus of the Muslim scholars testifies to its overall reliability and importance despite the presence of some weaker narrations.

This five-volume English translation makes the full content of Sunan Ibn Majah available to English-speaking readers for the first time in a complete and organized format. The translation adheres to a faithful rendering of the Arabic text into clear English prose, with careful attention to the legal and technical terminology that is essential for understanding the implications of the hadith for Islamic jurisprudence. Each narration is presented with its chain of narrators, and the volumes are organized according to Imam Ibn Majah's original chapter structure, which covers the book of the Sunnah (covering aqeedah and creed), purification, prayer, funerals, zakat, fasting, pilgrimage, marriage, divorce, food, sacrifices, clothing, medicine, Jihad, and a substantial section on manners, virtues, and historical events that provides important context not found in other hadith collections.

The unique value of Sunan Ibn Majah lies partly in its inclusion of hadith that address topics not covered in the other canonical collections, or that provide additional narrations and chains for hadith that appear elsewhere with fewer chains. Imam Ibn Majah included chapters on the virtues of the companions, the signs of the Day of Judgment, and various moral and ethical teachings that make his collection particularly rich in content beyond purely legal matters. Hadith scholars have noted that while Sunan Ibn Majah contains a higher proportion of weak narrations compared to Sahih al-Bukhari, Sahih Muslim, and Sunan An-Nasai, many of its hadith are strengthened by supporting chains found in other collections, and the overall collection remains a vital source for understanding the full spectrum of Prophetic guidance. This English translation set is produced with high-quality materials and durable binding, designed for long-term use in Islamic libraries, schools, universities, and personal study collections. It is an essential reference for English-speaking Muslims who want comprehensive access to the six canonical hadith collections in their own language.`,
    metaDescription: "English Translation of Sunan Ibn Majah 5 Vol Set with 4,341 hadith on fiqh, aqeedah, and manners. Unique narrations not in other canonical collections."
