    slug: "english-translation-of-the-meanings-of-sahih-muslim-7-volumes-set",
    description: `English Translation of the Meanings of Sahih Muslim — 7 Volumes Set is the complete and unabridged English translation of Sahih Muslim, the second most authoritative hadith collection in Sunni Islam after Sahih al-Bukhari, originally compiled by Imam Muslim ibn al-Hajjaj al-Qushayri (204-261 AH / 821-875 CE). Sahih Muslim contains approximately 7,563 narrations (including repetitions) selected from a corpus of approximately 300,000 hadith that Imam Muslim collected during his extensive travels throughout the Muslim world. The collection is renowned for its meticulous organization and the compiler's innovative approach to hadith presentation, which groups multiple narrations of the same hadith together under a single chapter heading, allowing the reader to see all the different chains of narration and wordings in one place.

This seven-volume English translation presents the complete text of Sahih Muslim in a faithful and readable English rendering that preserves the precision and nuance of the original Arabic. The translation is accompanied by extensive editorial apparatus, including explanatory notes that clarify difficult passages, identify the narrators in the chains of narration, explain the historical context of specific hadith, and highlight the legal and theological implications of important narrations. The seven-volume format allows for comfortable handling and study, with each volume covering a logical section of the collection. The books are organized according to Imam Muslim's original chapter structure, covering the book of faith (iman), purification, prayer, zakat, fasting, pilgrimage, marriage, divorce, trade, judicial matters, Jihad, virtues of the companions, manners, descriptions of the Prophet, signs of the Last Day, and many other topics.

Imam Muslim's methodology as a hadith compiler was distinguished by his precise approach to chain evaluation and his principle of presenting the full body of evidence for each hadith. Unlike some other compilers who presented narrations individually, Imam Muslim grouped all narrations of a given hadith together, including variations in wording and chain, so that the reader could evaluate the strength of the report by examining the totality of its evidence. He also developed the concept of the "connected" (muttasil) and "hanging" (mu'allaq) chain, and was particularly careful about distinguishing between the different types of narrators and their relative reliability. This English translation is produced with high-quality binding and paper designed for durability and ease of reading, making it suitable for institutional libraries, Islamic educational institutions, and serious personal collections. It is an indispensable resource for any English-speaking Muslim who wants to access the second most authoritative source of Prophetic traditions in its entirety.`,
